<div class="container mt-5">
  <h3 class="text-center">Early Life & Work</h3>
</div>

<div class="container">
  <div class="d-flex flex-row px-5">
    <div class="d-flex flex-column">
      <img src="http://web.engr.oregonstate.edu/~jov/images/emunch/arrival_of_the_mail_boat" class="img-fluid"> 
    </div>
    <div class="d-flex flex-column pl-1">
      <img src="http://web.engr.oregonstate.edu/~jov/images/emunch/the_sick_child" class="img-fluid"> 
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="d-flex flex-row px-5">
    <small class="text-muted">
      Left: <span class="p-name">Arrival of the Mail Boat</span>, 1890 | Right: <span class="p-name">The Sick Child</span>, 1885
    </small>
  </div>
  <div class="d-flex flex-row">
    <small class="text-muted px-5">
      Sources: (Left) arthive.com | (Right): edvardmunch.org
    </small>
  </div>
  <div class="d-flex flex-row mt-5">
      <div class="d-flex flex-column pl-5">
          <img src="http://web.engr.oregonstate.edu/~jov/images/emunch/self_portrait_w_cigarette" class="img-fluid">
      </div>
      <div class="col pr-5 my-auto">
          <p>
            Born in Norway, Munch was raised by his father and aunt after his mother and sister, Johanne Sophie, passed away. His sister's death had a lasting effect on Munch and he created several variants of <span class="p-name">The Sick Child</span>, which records the moments before his sister's death, throughout his career.
          </p>
          <p>
            Munch originally studied engineering at a technical college, but left to pursue being a painter. During his early years, he experimented with a variety of styles, such as Naturalism and Impressionism, but found these styles unsatisfactory for what he wanted to express through his paintings. His pursuit of art was a point of contention and criticism from his family and neighbors.
          </p>
          <p>
            In 1889, Munch traveled to Paris where he was inspired by 3 artists that would become influential in his own work: Paul Gaugin, Vincent Van Gogh, and Henri de Toulouse-Lautrec. That same year, his father died, leaving Munch financially responsible for his family and depressed.
          </p>
          <p><small class="text-muted align-bottom">
            <span class="p-name">Self-Portrait with Cigarette</span>, 1895<br>
            source: edvardmunch.org
          </small></p>
      </div>
  </div>
</div>

