      source: edvardmunch.org
      </small></p>
  </div>
  <div class="d-flex flex-row px-5">
    <div class="col mt-5">
          <p>
            By 1892, Munch had developed his characteristic style, different from the Naturalism and Impressionism styles he had been dabbling in before. 
            He spent the early 1890s in Berlin and gained widespread reception and recognition. It was here that his work began to evolve towards his mature style that he
            would later be known for. 
          </p>
          <p>
            <span class="p-name">The Scream</span> is Munch's most famous work and is widely interpreted to represent the universal anxiety of modern man. Exploration of the inner self, 
            rather than the exerior world, are common in Munch's paintings. However, it can be argued that Munch's exterior world is also represented tangentially 
            by the state of the interior world he portrays. Themes of love, loneliness, anxiety, sickness, and death are shown throughout his work. 
          </p>
      </div>
  </div>
